<subSubSection id="11FE2D80495B69EDE901F9557CAAB6DA" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph id="C40A84C0FFAD9DF82A0543FF53E6FD02" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">
<pageBreakToken id="C9C2FF664A68C2A57A5AFC2A2B851E4E" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" start="start">Description</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F1D3D3767340FA6A689F7AAAC73143B7" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">
Rhizome erect, rising at least 2-3 cm above ground, diameter 5-7 mm. Rhizome scales peltate or pseudopeltate, 2.5-3.0 
<normalizedToken id="824F71F5D5F01578F85606EF4248D66F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.7-0.9 mm, lanceolate with long falcate acumen. Fronds 30-80 
<normalizedToken id="C4F164FB89565F5ACB70E0E2D25F85D7" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
10-30 cm; stipes slender, 10-30 cm long, 0.1-0.2 cm across (at base), light brown; lamina deltoid, tripinnate to quadripinnate, 20-50 cm 
<normalizedToken id="DAE27428BB3D7B139B3A3BE440C38E4A" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
10-30 cm, papyraceous, bright green when dry, glabrous; pinnae at 30-35° to rachis, largest at base, overlapping, stalk 0.5 cm, including stalk 15-25 
<normalizedToken id="B74322F64D623EABDF4C233412AFB84F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-9 cm, lanceolate, first basiscopic pinnules of the lowest pinnae enlarged; ultimate segments 1-2 
<normalizedToken id="70BF68A1693F7592F1FC9BAB698422F8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5 cm, sessile or very short stalked, trapeziform, apex acute, margin without or with very weak cartilaginous border; deeply incised to less than 0.1 mm from veins; lobes narrowly oblanceolate, veins in lobes unbranched, light brown and not strongly contrasting with lamina, ending well below apex. Scales on rachis mostly at base of pinnae or pinnule, irregular triangular, basifixed. Sori apical on lobes, symmetric, not reflexed when dried, in one plane with lamina wings, 0.7-1.0 
<normalizedToken id="4B4F9A92A593B11DDEB79A24E1FA2BAA" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.4-0.5 mm, elliptic, widest at middle or slightly above, wider than the sterile lamina below sorus; inner indusium brownish green, thin and slightly transparent, usually shorter, sometimes 
<pageBreakToken id="50F36AB2ADD5FC04988E82E3C77F2A7F" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" start="start">equal</pageBreakToken>
to outer indusium, apex with narrow 0.2-0.3 mm long tongue, c. 1/2 length of sorus; outer indusium obtuse; sporangia 4-7 per sorus, capsule globose and rounded at apex, gradually narrowed toward base, indurated annulus cells 16-18, 
<normalizedToken id="C42399D7C899FE6C6F391A5BDEAFA870" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
equal; spores in polar view 26-30 
<normalizedToken id="932D575D74B6E959F034D87E65D37C0E" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, in lateral view 20-25 
<normalizedToken id="D1F9E98E439DCD38E6388ACD1434785B" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8F26B46F84FA19547B2EEA2AE9447CA6" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5E7123B900FFB35C2C5CB705BDCA3BE4" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="40D7EDC58B47378BC8AF4301A245C2F2" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">endemic to Fiji (Viti Levu).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CFE0D3FA19A66BA31F14D4FD672EDE17" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="0C1024263A4F5ED8F9B73D0DCA60E131" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D708A09C2F4CD00659F8367CA11B6EBC" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Terrestrial in dense forest, bank of creek, at 50-1200 m altitude.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9F46B15066C93A12EB99B771515DD886" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="70AC962D43B400D1A360E1410413A00F" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="11415244586C6A13F5CDF783CC29A1D3" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName id="9F190226DD0338789A9BAB9EA93ED5F5" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Saccolomataceae" genus="Orthiopteris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Orthiopteris ferulacea" order="Polypodiales" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferulacea">
<emphasis id="8DF0AE85EB8A27A752AA9F59D882E3F2" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Orthiopteris ferulacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the smallest species in the genus and the most easily recognizable among the species group with finely dissected fronds because of its relative small size and delicate and finely dissected frond. 
<taxonomicName id="B78DF447F3A10C32AE2E0B539674ED41" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Saccolomataceae" genus="Orthiopteris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Orthiopteris trichophylla" order="Polypodiales" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="trichophylla">
<emphasis id="3FB414544371C16E34400EDBA0CBAFEB" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Orthiopteris trichophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, similarly dissected, has larger fronds and funnel-shaped sori without narrow tongue, whereas sori of 
<taxonomicName id="A65519F1B04932051059836A44F39CE5" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Saccolomataceae" genus="Orthiopteris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Orthiopteris ferulacea" order="Polypodiales" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferulacea">
<emphasis id="7FED5E58A77693CE7CE6F85A0DECDD0E" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Orthiopteris ferulacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are elliptic with a narrow tongue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
